      <hedline>
        <hl1>Paths for Our Warming Planet</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Paul W Rosenberger letter says collapse of UN conference on climate change undermines US leadership position in rest of world (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The collapse of the United Nations conference on climate change (front page, Nov. 26) undermines the United States' leadership position in the rest of the world. The United States wants to attribute the failure of the conference to the European Union's unwillingness to be ''reasonable'' and compromise in order to reach agreement. But the United States' position reduced an already severely diluted Kyoto agreement to the point where no meaningful reduction in greenhouse gases would have been accomplished at all.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The collapse of the United Nations conference on climate change (front page, Nov. 26) undermines the United States' leadership position in the rest of the world. The United States wants to attribute the failure of the conference to the European Union's unwillingness to be ''reasonable'' and compromise in order to reach agreement. But the United States' position reduced an already severely diluted Kyoto agreement to the point where no meaningful reduction in greenhouse gases would have been accomplished at all.</p>
        <p>This is despite the fact that the United States is by far the world's biggest polluter and has done nothing to address the problem. This cynical disregard of a global danger and the cavalier dismissal of the rest of the world's effort to try to come to grips with this problem is a national disgrace.</p>
        <p>PAUL W. ROSENBERGER  Manhattan Beach, Calif., Nov. 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
